 {{nominated}}\n|-\n|[[APRA Music Awards of 2020|2020]] || \"Blackbird\" || Most Performed Blues & Roots Work of the Year<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.noise11.com/news/tones-and-i-leads-nominations-for-2020-virtual-apra-awards-20200407|title= Tones and I Leads Nominations for 2020 Virtual APRA Awards|website=Noise11|date=7 April 2020|accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://apraamcos.com.au/awards/2020-awards/apra-music-awards/|title=2020 Awards|website=APRA|date=7 April 2020|accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>|| {{pending}}\n|-\n{{end}}\n\n===ARIA Music Awards===\nThe [[ARIA Music Awards]] are annual awards, which recognises excellence, innovation, and achievement across all genres of [[Australian music]]. They commenced in 1987. Sultana has won one award from eleven nominations. (one pending)\n{{awards table}}\n!{{Abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\"| [[ARIA Music Awards of 2017|2017]] ||rowspan=\"3\"| ''Notion'' || [[ARIA Award for Best Independent Release|Best Independent Release]] || {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"4\" |<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ariaawards.com.au/history/year/2017 |title=ARIA Awards |work=[[ARIA Music Awards]] |accessdate=February 25, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[ARIA Award for Breakthrough Artist \u2013 Release|Breakthrough Artists]] || {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[ARIA Award for Best Blues and Roots Album|Best Blues and Roots Album]] || {{nom}}\n|-\n| Notion Tour || [[ARIA Award for Best Australian Live Act|Best Australian Live Act]] || {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"6\"| [[ARIA Music Awards of 2018|2018]] ||rowspan=\"2\"| ''Flow State'' || [[ARIA Award for Best Female Artist|Best Female Artist]] || {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"6\" |<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ariaawards.com.au/News/2018/And-The-ARIA-Award-Goes-To |title=ARIA Awards |work=[[ARIA Music Awards]] |accessdate=February 25, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[ARIA Award for Best Blues and Roots Album|Best Blues and Roots Album]] || {{won}}\n|-\n| Homecoming Tour || [[ARIA Award for Best Australian Live Act|Best Australian Live Act]] || {{nom}}\n|-\n| Tash Sultana for ''Flow State'' || [[ARIA Award for Producer of the Year|Producer of the Year]] || {{nom}}\n|-\n| Ben Lopez for ''Flow State'' || [[ARIA Award for Best Cover Art|Best Cover Art]] || {{nom}}\n|-\n| Glenn Mossop and Tash Sultana for \"Salvation\" || Best Video || {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[ARIA Music Awards of 2019|2019]] || \"Can't Buy Happiness\" || Best Soul/R&B Release || {{nom}}\n| <ref name=\"ARIA noms 2019\">{{cite web | url = https://ariaawards.com.au/news/2019/2019-aria-awards-nominated-artists-revealed | title = ARIA Awards: 2019 ARIA Awards Nominated Artists Revealed | publisher = Australian Recording Industry Association (ARIA) | date = 10 October 2019 | accessdate = 10 October 2019 }}</ref><ref name=\"ARIA 2019 Wins\">{{cite news | url = https://www.ariaawards.com.au/News/2019/2019-ARIA-Award-Winners-Announced | title = 2019 ARIA Award Winners Announced | publisher = Australian Recording Industry Association (ARIA) | date = 27 November 2019 | accessdate = 29 November 2019 }}</ref>\n|-\n{{end}}\n\n===Pop Awards===\nThe Pop Awards are presented annually by Pop Magazine, honoring the best in popular music.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pop-mag.com/2019-01-20/welcome-to-the-pop-awards-2019-the-second-annual-pop-awards/ |title=Welcome to the POP AWARDS 2019, the second annual Pop Awards |date=January 20, 2019 |first=Mai |last=Perkins |work=Pop Magazine |accessdate=February 25, 2019}}</ref> Tash Sultana has won two awards from two nominations and is the first artist to win multiple Pop Awards.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pop-mag.com/pop-awards |title=Pop Awards |work=Pop Magazine |accessdate=March 19, 2019}}</ref>\n{{awards table}}\n!{{Abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2019\n| ''Flow State''\n| Album Of The Year Award\n| {{won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"2\" |<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pop-awards.com/2019 |title=Pop Awards 2019, the 2nd annual Pop Awards |work=Pop Awards |accessdate=February 25, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| Tash Sultana\n| Emerging Artist Of The Year Award\n| {{won}}\n|}\n\n== Touring ==\n\n* Gemini Tour: Australia (2016)\n* Notion World Tour: Germany, United Kingdom, Netherlands, Australia, New Zealand (2016-17)\n* USA Tour 2017: United States (2017)\n* North American Tour: United States (2017)\n* Aus/NZ Tour: Australia, New Zealand (2017)\n* UK/Europe Tour: United Kingdom (2017)\n* Homecoming Tour: Australia (2017)\n* World Tour 2018: Europe, United States, Canada, New Zealand, United Kingdom (2018)\n* Flow State World Tour: Canada, United States, Europe, United Kingdom, Australia, New Zealand (2019)\n* Tash Sultana And Friends: Australia, New Zealand (2019)\n* UK And Europe 2020: United Kingdom, Europe (2020)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Tash Sultana}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sultana, Tash}}\n[[Category:Musicians from Melbourne]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1995 births]]\n[[Category:Genderqueer people]]\n[[Category:Australian people of Maltese descent]]\n[[Category:Australian multi-instrumentalists]]\n[[Category:Queer musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian singers]]\n[[Category:ARIA Award winners]]\n[[Category:Non-binary musicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp|small=yes}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Tash Sultana\n| background       = solo_singer\n| image            = Tash Sultana Piknik i Parken 2017 (185223).jpg\n| image_size       = \n| caption          = Tash Sultana performing in 2017\n| birth_name       = Natasha Sultana\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1995|6|15}}\n| birth_place      = [[Melbourne, Victoria]], Australia\n| genre            = [[Psychedelic rock]], [[alternative rock]], [[reggae rock]], [[lo-fi]]\n| occupation       = \n| instrument       = Guitar, vocals, bass, piano, keyboards, trumpet, drums, pan flute, mandolin, saxophone, percussion\n| years_active     = 2013\u2013present\n| label            = Lonely Lands Records, Mom+Pop Records, Sony Music Australia\n| website          = {{URL|https://www.tashsultana.com/}}\n}}\n \n'''Tash Sultana''' (born 15 June 1995) is an Australian singer-songwriter and multi-instrumentalist,<ref name=awareproject>{{cite web|url=http://awareproject.com.au/tash-sultana/|title=Tash Sultana Talks Gender Fluidity and Our Generation Accepting Diversity|publisher=Aware Project|date=4 April 2016|author=|accessdate=26 January 2017}}</ref> described as a \"one-person band\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/music/tash-sultana-review-welcome-to-the-jungle-of-the-one-woman-band-20161019-gs5ieb.html|title=Tash Sultana review: Welcome to the jungle of the one woman band|publisher=Sydney Morning Herald|date=19 October 2016 |author=Lucy Cormack|accessdate=26 January 2017}}</ref> Sultana's 2016 single \"Jungle\" was voted into third place in the [[Triple J Hottest 100, 2016]]; Sultana also had three songs voted into the [[Triple J Hottest 100, 2017]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newsweek.com/tash-sultana-will-leave-past-behind-flow-state-1060737|title=Tash Sultana will leave the past behind with ''Flow State''|last=Wynne|first=Kelly|date=7 August 2018|work=Newsweek|access-date=29 August 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nSultana grew up in [[Melbourne]], and has been playing guitar from the age of three,<ref name=awareproject/> beginning a career in music through [[street performance|busking]].<ref name=sbs>{{cite web|url=http://www.sbs.com.au/news/thefeed/article/2016/11/16/i-was-complete-drug-addict-musical-journey-tash-sultana|title=\"I was a complete drug addict\": The musical journey of Tash Sultana|publisher=The Feed|date=16 November 2016|author=Marc Fennell|accessdate=26 January 2017}}</ref> An active musician on [[Bandcamp]] since 2013,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tashsultana.bandcamp.com/music|title=Music - Tash Sultana|publisher=Bandcamp|date=|author=|accessdate=26 January 2017}}</ref> Sultana's recordings were viewed millions of times on YouTube in 2016. Sultana's EP, ''[[Notion (EP)|Notion]]'', was released on 23 September 2016, followed by a sold-out world tour in early 2017.\n\n==Personal life==\nAustralian with half-[[Malta|Maltese]] ancestry, Sultana was born and grew up in [[Melbourne]], and received a guitar from their grandfather at the age of three. They can play 20 instruments including [[guitar]], [[Bass (instrument)|bass]], [[trumpet]], [[flute]], [[percussion]] and [[saxophone]]. A self-described drug addict, Sultana developed drug-induced [[psychosis]] at the age of 17 and had to undergo several months of therapy to recover.<ref name=sbs/> Sultana is [[Genderqueer|nonbinary]] and uses the pronoun ''[[Singular they|they]]''.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Tash Sultana playing at 170 Russell.jpg|thumb|Sultana playing guitar at a live performance in Melbourne]]\n\n=== Early career: \"Jungle\" and home, busking videos ===\nUnable to find regular work, Sultana turned to [[busking]] on the streets of Melbourne to make a living.<ref name=\"sbs\" /> From 2008 to 2012, Sultana was the vocalist of the band Mindpilot with Patrick O'Brien, Emily Daye and David Herbert. This band won several Battles of the Bands competitions in Melbourne. The band split in 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/mindpilottheband|title=Mindpilot - Facebook|last=|first=|date=|website=Mindpilot Facebook|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Sultana shared a video on [[social media]] of \"Jungle\" that garnered one million views within five days.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tonedeaf.com.au/478469/tash-sultanas-new-video-gets-a-million-views-in-five-days.htm|title=Tash Sultana Shares Video, Gets a Million Views in Five Days|publisher=Tonedeaf|date=3 May 2016|author=Greg Moskovitch|accessdate=26 January 2017}}</ref> In the same year, they won the [[J Award]] for Unearthed Artist of the Year and had two tracks voted into the [[Triple J Hottest 100, 2016]]: \"Jungle\" (No. 3) and \"Notion\" (No. 32). Both are singles from the [[Extended play|EP]] ''[[Notion (EP)|Notion]]''. Sultana performed at the [[Woodford Folk Festival]], [[Southbound (festival)|Southbound]], and [[St Jerome's Laneway Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://themusic.com.au/news/all/2017/01/04/tash-sultana-sells-out-entire-us-tour-over-a-month-out-from-shows/|title=Tash Sultana Sells Out Entire US Tour Over A Month Out From Shows|publisher=TheMusic.com.au|date=4 January 2017|author=Uppy Chatterjee|accessdate=26 January 2017}}</ref> Sultana is managed by Lemon Tree Music with whom they signed in June 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://themusic.com.au/news/all/2016/06/20/tash-sultana-signs-management-deal-with-lemon-tree-music/|title=Tash Sultana Signs Management Deal With Lemon Tree Music|website=theMusic|access-date=1 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nA home recording of the single \"Jungle\" has gained over 40 million views. Sultana went into the studio with producer Nikita Miltiadou and began working on the [[Extended play|EP]] release ''[[Notion (EP)|Notion]]''. In September 2016, they released the EP through their own independent record label, Lonely Lands Records. The EP reached a peak position of number 8 on the ARIA Charts.\n\n=== 2016-17: Debut world tour, and singles ===\nDue to the success of ''[[Notion (EP)|Notion]]'', Sultana announced a world tour, including hundreds of shows in Australia, Europe, New Zealand, and the United Kingdom. Their father resigned from his job in order to become their [[Road crew|roadie]]. Working with Miltiadou in April 2017, Sultana released \"[[Murder to the Mind]]\", the first single since the release of ''Notion''. It reached number 59 on the Australian Singles chart.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.abc.net.au/triplej/musicnews/s4655337.htm |title=PSA: Tash Sultana's new single dropping today on triple j |last= |first= |date= |website=ABC News |access-date=}}</ref> Not long after the release of \"Murder to the Mind\", Sultana was diagnosed with [[laryngitis]], and was forced to cancel and postpone shows across Australia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/tashsultanaofficial|title=Tash Sultana's Facebook page|last=|first=|date=|website=Facebook|access-date=}}{{Dead link|date=June 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }}</ref>\n\nIn a June 2017 interview, Sultana told Fairfax that the debut album is slated for release in April 2018, after which they had planned to tour, record a second album, tour again, and then take a break and return to normal life.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://musicfeeds.com.au/news/heres-expect-tash-sultanas-debut-album/|title=Here's When To Expect Tash Sultana's Debut Album|last=Murphy|first=Sam|date=18 July 2017|website=Music Feeds|accessdate=18 July 2017}}</ref> On 25 July 2017, Sultana announced the Homecoming Tour. As part of the tour, they visited Adelaide (Entertainment Centre), Sydney (Hordern Pavilion), Fremantle (Arts Centre), Margaret River (3 Oceans Winery), Melbourne (Margaret Court Arena) and Noosa (Noosa Sporting Grounds), with the Pierce Brothers and Willow Beats as supporting acts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://musicfeeds.com.au/news/tash-sultana-announces-2017-homecoming-tour/#/slide/1|title=Tash Sultana Announces 2017 Homecoming Tour|last=|first=|date=26 July 2017|website=Music Feeds|access-date=26 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2017, Sultana announced the premiere of a new single \"[[Mystik]]\" on [[Triple J|triple j]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Tencic|first1=Nat|title=Tash Sultana makes US TV debut, talks new single 'Mystik' and a \"small hiatus\"|url=http://www.abc.net.au/triplej/news/musicnews/tash-sultana-us-tv-debut-new-single-mystik-small-hiatus/9014700|website=triple j|accessdate=25 October 2017|date=4 October 2017}}</ref> Also in October, Sultana made a television debut on ''[[Late Night with Seth Meyers]]'', performing \"Jungle\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Desk|first1=BWW News|title=VIDEO: Tash Sultana Makes U.S. TV Debut Performing 'Jungle' on LATE NIGHT|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwmusic/article/VIDEO-Tash-Sultana-Makes-US-TV-Debut-Performing-Jungle-on-LATE-NIGHT-20171003|website=Broadway World|accessdate=25 October 2017}}</ref> They were nominated for four [[ARIA]] Awards: Breakthrough Artist, Best Independent Release, Best Blues and Roots Album and Best Australian Live Act).<ref name=\"Amplify\">{{cite web|title=TASH SULTANA nominated for FOUR ARIA AWARDS|url=http://amnplify.com.au/tash-sultana-nominated-for-four-aria-awards/|website=Amnplify|accessdate=25 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the Homecoming Tour, Sultana continued work on their debut LP, ''[[Flow State (album)|Flow State]]'', released on 31 August 2018.<ref name=\"npr\">{{cite web |last=Abshire |first=Emily |title=Tash Sultana Finds 'Salvation' In The Form Of Studio Time And Skydiving |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/allsongs/2018/06/21/622247959/tash-sultana-finds-salvation-in-the-form-of-studio-time-and-skydiving |website=NPR.org |accessdate=22 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== 2018: Debut LP ''Flow State'' ===\nOn 13 June 2018, Sultana sent out a Facebook private message to selected fans, with a video of a sneak peek of a new single titled \"Salvation\", accompanied by footage in the studio.{{cn|date=June 2018}} Sultana announced in June 2018 that the new single would premier on [[Triple J]] on 21 June, and was released on 22 June.<ref name=\"npr\" />\n\nOn 21 June 2018, they announced the album's future release date of 31 August, 2018, and made pre-orders available. Sultana also announced the album's tracklist, including the already-released tracks [[Mystik|\"Mystik\"]], [[Murder to the Mind|\"Murder To The Mind\"]], \"Harvest Love\" and \"Free Mind\". \n\nThe album was released on 31 August 2018, and charted at No. 2 on the ARIA Albums Charts.<ref name=\"AUS\" />\n\n=== 2019: ''Flow State'' Tour, \"Can't Buy Happiness\", \"Daydreaming\" and \"Talk It Out\" ===\nIn February 2019, Sultana played their biggest Australian shows yet, including a sold out show at Melbourne's [[Sidney Myer Music Bowl]], and Brisbane's [[Riverstage]]. Sultana's first release for 2019 was the standalone single \"Can't Buy Happiness\", released on 4 April. Then, on 10 July, Sultana released their first collaboration \"Talk It Out\", which featured Australian singer Matt Corby. Sultana's final release for 2019 was the single \"Daydreaming\", a collaboration with [[Milky Chance]].\n\n=== 2020: Transition to live band format, and \"Pretty Lady\" ===\nEarly in 2020, Sultana announced they were recruiting for live band members on social media, and that they'd play no more solo performances for the foreseeable future. On 26 February, Sultana played their final solo live show at Melbourne's Sidney Myer Music Bowl as part of the one-day music festival Down To Earth. The show was raising funds for bushfire relief, and included performances by Gang of Youths, Angus & Julia Stone and more.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/triplej/news/musicnews/gang-of-youths-tash-sultana-all-star-fire-relief-concert/11849670|title=Gang of Youths, Tash Sultana, Angus & Julia Stone head up all-star fire relief concert|last=Newstead|first=Al|date=2020-01-08|website=triple j|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2020, the musician announced they'd found band members, and would be releasing their first single for 2020, \"Pretty Lady\" on 9 April. The track was premiered on triple j Breakfast the same day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/triplej/news/musicnews/tash-sultana-new-song-pretty-lady-matt-corby-live-band-new-album/12134484|title=First Spin: Tash Sultana reunites with Matt Corby for 'Pretty Lady'|last=Newstead|first=Al|date=2020-04-09|website=triple j|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> Subsequently, that day, Sultana released the music video, featuring a selection of fans, friends and family from across the world dancing.\n\n==Discography==\n[[File:Tash Sultana playing trumpet at her live show.jpg|thumb|Sultana playing the trumpet on stage]]\n===Album===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:16em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"8\"| Peak chart positions\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"|[[ARIA Charts|AUS]]<br /><ref name=\"AUS\"/>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"|[[Canadian Albums Chart|CAN]]<br/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fyimusicnews.ca/articles/2018/09/10/eminem-weeks-kamikaze-king|title=Eminem Is This Week's 'Kamikaze' King|work=FYIMusicNews|accessdate=11 September 2018}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"|[[GfK Entertainment Charts|GER]]<br /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.offiziellecharts.de/album-details-363317|title=Tash Sultana Discografie|publisher=Offizielle Deutsche Charts|accessdate=9 September 2018}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"|[[Irish Albums Chart|IRE]]<br /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irma.ie/index.cfm?page=irish-charts&chart=Albums|title=Albums Chart: 7 September 2018|publisher=Irish Charts|accessdate=11 September 2018}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"|[[MegaCharts|NLD]]<br /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://dutchcharts.nl/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Tash+Sultana|title=Tash Sultana Discografie|publisher=Dutch Charts|accessdate=9 September 2018}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"|[[Official New Zealand Music Chart|NZ]]<br /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://nztop40.co.nz/chart/albums?chart=4521|title=NZ Top 40 Albums Chart|publisher=[[Recorded Music NZ]]|date=10 September 2018|accessdate=9 September 2018}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"|[[UK Albums Chart|UK]]<br /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/52914/tash-sultana/|title=Tash Sultana Official Charts Archive|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=9 September 2018}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"|[[Billboard 200|US]]<br /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/tash-sultana/chart-history/billboard-200|title=Tash Sultana Chart History: Billboard 200|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=11 September 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Flow State (album)|Flow State]]''\n|\n* Released: 31 August 2018\n* Label: Lonely Lands\n* Formats: [[Compact disc|CD]], [[Music download|digital download]], [[Phonograph record|vinyl]]\n| 2 || 22 || 18 || 67 || 18 || 12 || 67 || 51\n|}\n\n===Extended play===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:16em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"1\"| Peak chart positions\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"|[[ARIA Charts|AUS]]<br /><ref name=\"AUS\">Peaks in Australia:\n* All except noted: {{cite web|url=http://australian-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Tash+Sultana|title=australian-charts.com \u2013 Discography Tash Sultana|publisher=Hung Medien|accessdate=28 January 2017}}\n* \"Murder to the Mind\": {{cite web|url=https://www.auspop.com.au/2017/04/aria-chart-watch-418/|title=ARIA Chart Watch #418|date=29 April 2017|publisher=auspOp|accessdate=29 April 2017}}\n* \"Mystik\": {{cite web|url=https://www.auspop.com.au/2017/10/aria-chart-watch-442/|title=ARIA Chart Watch #442|date=14 October 2017|publisher=auspOp|accessdate=14 October 2017}}\n* \"Salvation\": {{cite web|url=https://australian-charts.com//forum.asp?todo=viewthread&id=55271&pages=|title=ARIA Chartifacts 2-July-2018|date= October 30, 2017|accessdate=November 29, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Yin Yang''\n|\n* Released: 2013\n* Label: Tash Sultana\n* Formats: digital download\n| \u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Notion (EP)|Notion]]''\n|\n* Released: 23 September 2016\n* Label: Lonely Lands\n* Formats: CD, digita