{"title_page": "The Public's Radio", "text_new": "{{short description|Public radio network serving Rhode Island}}\n{{Infobox radio station\n|name               = The Public's Radio\n|image              = [[File:Thepublicsradio-logo.jpg|200px|none]]\n|area               = [[Rhode Island]], [[South Coast (Massachusetts)|Massachusetts South Coast]]\n|branding           = \n|slogan             = \n|frequency          = [[WNPN]] 89.3 [[Newport, Rhode Island|Newport]]<br>[[WELH]] 88.1 [[Providence, Rhode Island|Providence]]<br>[[WNPE (FM)|WNPE]] 102.7 [[Narragansett Pier, Rhode Island|Narragansett Pier]]<br>[[WCVY]] 91.5 [[Coventry, Rhode Island|Coventry]]\n|translator         = \n|airdate            = May 1, 1998\n|share              = \n|share as of        = \n|share source       = \n|format             = [[Public Radio]]\n|language           = English\n|affiliations       = [[NPR]]<br>[[Public Radio International]]<br>[[American Public Media]]\n|owner              = Rhode Island Public Radio, Inc\n|licensee           = \n|sister_stations    = \n|webcast            = {{listenlive|http://ripr.org/streaming}}\n|website            = {{URL|https://thepublicsradio.org/}}\n}}\n'''Rhode Island Public Radio''', [[doing business as]] '''The Public's Radio,''' is the [[NPR]] member [[radio network]] for the state of [[Rhode Island]] and southeastern [[Massachusetts]].  Its studios are located in the historic [[Union Station (Providence)|Union Station]] in downtown Providence.  The network airs a format of news and talk from NPR, such as ''[[Morning Edition]]'', ''[[On Point]]'', and ''[[All Things Considered]]'', as well as extensive local news coverage.\n\n==Local programming==\nIn addition to NPR, APM and other public radio programming from national sources, RIPR has dedicated reporters covering specific beats, including [http://ripr.org/programs/politics Politics], [http://ripr.org/programs/pulse Health Care], [http://ripr.org/programs/education-blog Education], the [http://ripr.org/category/environment Environment], and [http://ripr.org/category/arts-culture Arts & Culture].  RIPR also produces local segments including:\n* [http://ripr.org/programs/political-roundtable ''Political Roundtable''] with Ian Donnis, Scott Mackay & Maureen Moakley every Friday.\n* [http://ripr.org/programs/scott-mackays-commentary Scott MacKay's Weekly Commentary'']\n* [http://ripr.org/programs/i-believe-new-england ''This I Believe: New England''] with Frederic Reamer.  A local take on the famous [http://thisibelieve.org ''This I Believe''] series of essays.\n* [http://ripr.org/programs/made-rhode-island ''Made in Rhode Island''] an ongoing occasional series looking at manufacturing in the state.\n* [http://ripr.org/programs/one-square-mile ''One Square Mile''] an annual special week-long series, taking an in-depth look at one city or town in Rhode Island.  Previous OSM series include: Central Falls, Bristol, Woonsocket, West Warwick, Block Island, Narragansett Bay itself, and Newport.\n* [http://ripr.org/policy-and-pinot ''Policy & Pinot''] an ongoing occasional series taped live at the [http://www.providenceathenaeum.org Providence Athenaeum Library] focusing on various topics.\n\n==Broadcast stations==\nThe network's primary signal, [[WNPN]] 89.3FM in [[Newport, Rhode Island|Newport]], broadcasts from the old [[WLNE-TV]] tower in [[Tiverton, Rhode Island|Tiverton]] and covers most of Rhode Island and the [[South Coast (Massachusetts)|Massachusetts South Coast]].  It is the tallest active FM broadcast transmitter in Rhode Island (measured in height above sea level). Only [[WLVO (FM)|WLVO]]'s ''auxiliary'' site on Peck Hill in [[Johnston, Rhode Island]] is taller.\n\nSmaller repeater signals provide additional coverage in Providence ([[WELH]]), South County ([[WNPE (FM)|WNPE]]), and Coventry ([[WCVY]]).\n\n===Technology===\n\n[[WNPN]] transmits using a [[Nautel]] GV15 transmitter with 10,187 watts transmitter power output (TPO) to make 7,000 watts effective radiated power (ERP). A [http://www.shively.com Shively Labs] 6016 four-panel antenna array is used; the antenna is fairly directional, with nulls to avoid prohibited interference to/from [[WQPH]] 89.3FM [[Shirley, Massachusetts]] to the north-northwest, and to [[WPKT]] 89.1FM [[Norwich, Connecticut]] to the west-southwest. An Omnia 9 FM/HD processor from [[The Telos Alliance]] is used to keep audio levels consistent. The station broadcasts in digital [[HD Radio]] although {{as of|2018|8}} no [[multicast]] HD2 or HD3 channels are transmitted. A 67&nbsp;kHz [[subcarrier]] is transmitted for the Massachusetts [[Radio Reading Service]] ''[http://www.audiblelocalledger.org/ Audible Local Ledger]''.\n\n===[[HD Radio]]===\n[[WNPN]] 89.3FM and [[WNPE (FM)|WNPE]] 102.7FM broadcast in [[HD Radio]], simulcasting the analog signal on the HD1 channel.  [[WELH]] 88.1FM and [[WCVY]] 91.5 do not broadcast in HD Radio.\n\nFrom March 2013 until February 2018, [[MVYradio]] leased the HD2 multicast channel of [[WNPE (FM)|WNPE]] to broadcast a modified content stream of [[WMVY]] 88.7FM on Martha's Vineyard, which could also be heard on [[W243AI]] 96.5FM, a lower powered [[FM translator]] transmitting from the roof of Newport Hospital.<ref>[http://ripr.org/post/theec-ripr-mvyradio-leverage-hd-radio-fm-translators RIPR & MVYradio Leverage HD Radio for FM Translators]</ref>  Afterwards, [[WNPE (FM)|WNPE]] discontinued the HD2 broadcast, but continued HD Radio operations for its main HD1 channel.\n\n{| class=\"toccolours\" class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Station\n! Frequency\n! City of license\n! First air date\n! ERP\n! HAAT\n! Facility ID\n! Coordinates\n! Call sign meaning\n! Former call signs\n! Owner\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top; text-align: left;\"\n| '''[[WNPN]]'''\n| 89.3&nbsp;MHz<br>FM & HD\n| [[Newport, Rhode Island|Newport]]\n| June 10, 2006<ref name=\"by2009\">{{cite book|title=Broadcasting & Cable Yearbook 2009|year=2009|page=D-273|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-YB/2009/Radio-GA-MT-BC-YB-2009.pdf|accessdate=August 7, 2018}}</ref>\n| 7,000 watts<br>(directional)\n| {{convert|254|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}\n| 163899\n| {{coord|41|35|48.00|N| 71|11|24.00|W|type:landmark_scale:2000|name=WNPN}}\n| Derived from \"'''N'''ewport, '''P'''rovidence, '''N'''ew Bedford\".\n| WUMD (2006\u20132017)<br>WXNI (2017\u20132018)\n| Rhode Island Public Radio\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top; text-align: left;\"\n| '''WNPE'''\n| 102.7&nbsp;MHz<br>FM & HD\n| [[Narragansett Pier, Rhode Island|Narragansett Pier]]\n| July 15, 1989<ref name=projo-wrnifmstart>1996 Providence Journal Almanac</ref>\n| 1,950 watts<br>(omni)\n| {{convert|69|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}\n| 22874\n| {{coord|41|25|27|N|71|28|38|W|type:landmark_scale:2000|name=WNPE}}\n| Similar to [[WNPN]].\n| WPJB (1989\u20131997)<br>WAKX (1997\u20132007)<br>WRNI-FM (2007-2018)<br>WRNI (2018)\n| Rhode Island Public Radio\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top; text-align: left;\"\n| '''[[WELH]]'''<sup>1</sup>\n| 88.1&nbsp;MHz<br>FM only\n| [[Providence, Rhode Island|Providence]]\n| February 1995\n| 4,000 watts<br>(directional)\n| {{convert|41|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}\n| 66656\n| {{coord|41|51|26.7|N|71|19|5.6|W|type:landmark_scale:2000|name=WELH}}\n| '''W'''h'''E'''e'''L'''er Sc'''H'''ool\n| (none)\n| [[The Wheeler School]]\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top; text-align: left;\"\n| '''[[WCVY]]'''<sup>2</sup>\n| 91.5&nbsp;MHz<br>FM only\n| [[Coventry, Rhode Island|Coventry]]\n| October 19, 1978<ref name=by2003>{{cite book|title=Broadcasting & Cable Yearbook 2003-2004|year=2003|page=D-417|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-YB/2003-04/D-Radio-NE-TER-BC-YB-2003-04.pdf|accessdate=October 10, 2011}}</ref> \n| 200 watts<br>(omni)\n| {{convert|11|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}\n| 14229\n| {{coord|41|41|10|N|71|35|37|W|type:landmark_scale:2000|name=WCVY}}\n| '''C'''o'''V'''entr'''Y'''\n| (none)\n| Coventry Public Schools\n|}\n\nNote:\n*<sup>1</sup> WELH airs student-produced programming from 7pm-10pm Sundays, with The Public's Radio programming airing at all other times.\n*<sup>2</sup> WCVY airs its own programming out of [[Coventry High School (Coventry, Rhode Island)|Coventry High School]] from 2 to 8 p.m. on school days, with The Public's Radio programming airing at all other times.\n* The network's programming is also available on [http://www.fullchannel.com Full Channel Digital Cable] channel 799 in Bristol, Warren and Barrington.\n\n==History==\nIn the 1990s, a group of Rhode Islanders formed the Foundation for Ocean State Public Radio in order to bring a local public radio station to the state. Clare Gregorian was described as the \"driving force\" behind the idea.<ref>http://www.providencejournal.com/news/20180429/clare-gregorian-driving-force-behind-ripr-dies-at-80</ref> At the time, Rhode Island was the only state in [[New England]] (traditionally one of the bedrocks of support for NPR) and one of only two in the entire country (the other being [[Delaware]]) that did not have a full-service NPR station within its borders. Most of the state got at least a grade B signal from Boston's [[WGBH (FM)|WGBH]] (with Providence itself receiving a city-grade signal) and [[WBUR]].  After a few years of looking, they found a partner in [[Boston University]], owner of WBUR.  BU agreed to buy [[WRPA (AM)|WRCP]] (1290 [[AM broadcasting|AM]]), a 5,000-watt station that had been on the air since [[1947 in radio|1947]], for $1.9 million; the foundation conducted a statewide drive to help raise the funds.  For many years, 1290 AM had been known as WICE, but switched to [[Portugal|Portuguese]] programming as WRCP in [[1983 in radio|1983]].\n\nOn May 1, 1998, WRCP's calls officially changed to WRNI, and the license was officially transferred to the '''WRNI Foundation,''' a separate fundraising group set up by WBUR to handle local underwriting.\n\nEven though BU doubled WRNI's transmission power to 10,000 watts, its signal was not strong enough to reach the southern and western portion of the state (though it provides a city-grade signal to [[Newport, Rhode Island|Newport]], southern Rhode Island's biggest city).  Accordingly, in 1999, BU bought WERI (1230 AM) in Westerly, which had been on the air since [[1949 in radio|1949]].  BU changed WERI's calls to WXNI, and made it a full-time satellite of WRNI.  The station brought a city-grade NPR signal to southern Rhode Island for the first time ever.\n\nBU and WBUR had very big plans for WRNI at first. It moved WRNI from its longtime studio on Douglas Avenue to a state-of-the-art facility at Union Station.  It also started a daily two-hour local news magazine, ''One Union Station.''  <ref name=\"Fybush\">[http://www.fybush.com/NERW/2004/040920/nerw.html NorthEast Radio Watch by Scott Fybush<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>  It also had plans to set up a third station to fill the gaps in WXNI's 1,000-watt signal.<ref name=\"Current\">[http://www.current.org/radio/radio0418rhodeisland.shtml Current.org | Struggle over WBUR's Rhode Island stations, 2004<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> However, budget problems brought on by the [[September 11, 2001 attacks]] forced ''One Union Station's'' cancellation. It was replaced with a one-hour news magazine that was canceled in 2004. At that point, WRNI's local operations were significantly cut back, with most of the station's staff either laid off or transferred to Boston. As a result, WRNI's schedule became almost identical to that of WBUR.\n\n===Controversy over sale of 1290AM===\nOn September 17, 2004, with no advance warning, WBUR Group general manager Jane Christo announced that WRNI and WXNI were being put on the market. She wouldn't give any specifics, only saying that it was time for Rhode Islanders to buy the stations if they wanted to keep NPR programming in the state.<ref name=\"Fybush\"/>  Indeed, WBUR claimed that it never intended to operate WRNI on a long-term basis, and had only intended to help develop it into a self-sustaining service.<ref name=\"Current\"/>\n\nThe reaction in Rhode Island was, not surprisingly, hostile. In an editorial, ''[[The Providence Journal]]'' said that WBUR had made numerous long-term commitments to WRNI. The ''Journal'' claimed that if the station's local backers had to buy WRNI, it would be tantamount to buying the station twice.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.projo.com/opinion/editorials/content/projo_20040919_19edwr.10caf3.html|title=Editorial: Broadcast betrayal |work=Providence Journal|date=September 19, 2004|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080301105211/http://www.projo.com/opinion/editorials/content/projo_20040919_19edwr.10caf3.html|archivedate=March 1, 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe announcement led state attorney general [[Patrick C. Lynch|Patrick Lynch]] to open an investigation into WBUR and WRNI.<ref name=\"LynchGlobe\">{{cite news|author=Peoples, Steve| url=http://www.beloblog.com/ProJo_Blogs/newsblog/archives/2006/11/attorney_genera_1.html | title=Attorney general closes WBUR investigation | work=Providence Journal|date=November 20, 2006|accessdate=September 22, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn September 27, BU interim president [[Aram Chobanian]] delayed the sale of WRNI and WXNI, citing concerns raised by both Lynch and [[Governor of Rhode Island|Rhode Island Governor]] [[Don Carcieri]].  Memos obtained by ''[[The Boston Globe]]'' revealed that WBUR felt the Rhode Island stations were money bleeders, and had decided to either lease or sell the stations at the earliest opportunity.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.boston.com/ae/tv/articles/2004/09/28/bu_delays_sale_of_ri_radio_stations | work=The Boston Globe | first=Mark | last=Jurkowitz | title=BU delays sale of R.I. radio stations | date=September 28, 2004}}</ref>  The furor over the WRNI sale was one factor in Christo's resignation almost a month later.<ref>[http://www.current.org/radio/radio0419wbur.shtml Current.org | Christo resigns at WBUR, 2004<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nIn June [[2005 in radio|2005]], BU took WRNI and WXNI off the market.  It promised to hire a full-time general manager based in Providence, and also stepped up local news coverage.  As a result, Lynch closed his investigation in November 2006.<ref name=\"LynchGlobe\"/>\n\n===Independence from Boston University===\nOn March 21, 2007, WBUR announced that it was selling WRNI to Rhode Island Public Radio (formerly the Foundation for Ocean State Public Radio) for $2 million. Rhode Island Public Radio also announced it was buying WAKX (102.7 [[FM broadcasting|FM]]) in [[Narragansett Pier, Rhode Island|Narragansett Pier]] from [[Davidson Media Group]] to serve as a repeater for WRNI in southern Rhode Island.<ref>{{cite news|author=Smith, Andy| url=http://green.tmcnet.com/news/2007/03/23/2439642.htm| title=R.I. group to buy WRNI|date=March 23, 2007|work=Providence Journal}}</ref> WAKX, which signed on in 1989, had been a [[smooth jazz]] station (though its call letters referred to a former simulcast of [[WWKX]], which lasted from 1997 to 2005).  As part of the sale agreement, BU will continue to provide engineering and programming assistance to RIPR for five years.\n\nRIPR officially took control of WAKX on May 17, 2007; changing the calls to WRNI-FM. The addition of WRNI-FM made WXNI redundant, and BU has sold that station separately to Diponti Communications, which renamed it [[WBLQ (AM)|WBLQ]].  RIPR took control of WRNI on September 1, 2008.\n\nRIPR registered the domain name ''ripr.org'' on February 13, 2007; the site was live as of June 2007.\n\n===Migration to FM===\n[[File:WNPN Air Studio.jpg|thumb|right|The Public's Radio Studio A, where local newscasts originate daily.]]\nRecognizing the long-term challenges of AM broadcasting,<ref>[http://www.radioworld.com/news-and-business/0002/is-am-radio-still-relevant/322673 \"Is AM Radio Still Relevant?\" Radio World, August 30, 2009]</ref> and the general expectation by public radio listeners that public radio stations transmit on the noncommercial end of the FM band (88.1-91.9&nbsp;MHz), in 2011 WRNI began to expand into a statewide network of FM signals.  Accordingly, it also began branding itself exclusively as \"Rhode Island Public Radio.\"\n\n'''91.5FM''' First, in July 2011, RIPR entered an agreement with [[WCVY]] (91.5 FM), which is owned & operated by [[Coventry High School (Coventry, Rhode Island)|Coventry High School]] and covers the Kent County region. Previously, because WCVY did not broadcast 24/7, they had been forced, under [https://www.law.cornell.edu/cfr/text/47/73.561 FCC rule 73.561(b)], to \"share-time\" 16 hours per day of the frequency with the now-defunct [[Religious broadcasting|religious]] station [[WRJI]]. After WRJI lost its license, RIPR assisted WCVY in \"reclaiming\" the frequency for 24/7 operation.  WCVY still airs its own student-created programming on weekdays from 2-8p.m. when school is in session, and RIPR fills the remainder of the time to avoid another \"share-time\" challenge.<ref name=nerw-wcvyripr>{{cite news|last=Fybush|first=Scott|authorlink=|title=Merlin Drops 101.9 Clues|url=http://www.fybush.com/NERW/2011/110711/nerw.html|accessdate=October 10, 2011|newspaper=NorthEast Radio Watch|date=July 11, 2011}}</ref>\n\n'''88.1FM''' Then, on October 8, 2011, RIPR signed a 10-year lease with [[The Wheeler School]], a K-12 private day school and owner of [[WELH]] (88.1 FM).<ref>[http://www.radiosurvivor.com/2011/08/22/the-wheeler-school-to-lease-fm-airwaves-to-rhode-island-public-radio/ \"The Wheeler School to Lease FM Airwaves to Rhode Island Public Radio\"] Jennifer Waits, ''Radio Survivor'', August 22, 2011</ref> RIPR's content would be heard 24/7 on 88.1 in Providence except for a student-produced sports talk radio midnight-3 Saturday mornings.  The remainder of Wheeler's student media was migrated to internet radio and, more recently, to [http://www.wheelerschoolbroadcasting.org/ internet video projects].\n\nAs part of this new lease, the previous lease tenants on 88.1, [[WBRU-LP|Brown Student Radio]], and [[Latino Public Radio]], each broadcasting a limited number of hours each day, were displaced:\n\n*BSR began an internet radio station \"[http://www.bsrlive.com BSRlive]\" and, in January 2015, was granted an FCC license for an LPFM station [https://fccdata.org/?facid=&call=wbru&ccode=1&city=&state=&country=US&arn=&party=&party_type=LICEN WBRU-LP] on 101.1FM in Providence, in conjunction with [[Providence Community Radio]] and [[AS220]].<ref name=bsr-lpfm>{{cite news|last=Ahlquist|first=Steve|title=New low-power FM community radio station coming to Providence|url=http://www.rifuture.org/new-low-power-fm-community-radio-station-coming-to-providence/|accessdate=November 13, 2015|newspaper=RIfuture.org|date=November 13, 2015}}</ref><ref>[https://as220.org/101-1-fm-community-radio/ \"AS220: 101.1 FM Community Radio!\"] November 9, 2015</ref>\n*Latino Public Radio signed a lease with RIPR to broadcast on RIPR's 1290AM signal, WRNI,<ref name=projo-wrnishuffle>{{cite news|last=Ziner|first=Karen Lee|title=R.I. Latino radio station going 24/7 in new place|url=http://www.projo.com/news/content/LATINO_PUBLIC_RADIO_10-07-11_R4QO3C9_v29.70439.html|accessdate=October 10, 2011|newspaper=[[The Providence Journal]]|date=October 7, 2011|archiveurl=http://www.latinopublicradioconsortium.org/index.php?s=7394&item=21203|archivedate=October 7, 2011}}</ref><ref name=rinpr-wrnishuffle>{{cite news|last=Harrison|first=Elisabeth|title=Changes ahead for radio in Rhode Island|url=http://www.publicbroadcasting.net/wrni/news.newsmain/article/0/0/1861788/Top.Stories/Changes.ahead.for.radio.in.Rhode.Island|accessdate=October 10, 2011|newspaper=WRNI.org|date=October 10, 2011}}</ref> and moved to 1290AM the same day RIPR moved to 88.1FM.  In addition to allowing LPR to broadcast 24/7, it also gave them a larger signal.<ref>Until late 2010, WELH was only a 150-watt signal, much smaller than the 4, 000-watt signal it is today. See [http://fccdata.org/?appid=205223&facid=66656 \"FCCdata.org file on WELH\"] and [http://fccdata.org/?facid=48308 \"FCCdata.org file on WRNI-AM\"] for comparison.</ref>\n\n'''89.3FM:''' Most recently, in January 2017, RIPR announced a deal with the [[University of Massachusetts, Dartmouth]] to purchase [[WNPN|WUMD]] (89.3 FM).<ref>[http://ripr.org/post/ri-public-radio-acquiring-umass-dartmouth-radio-station \"RI Public Radio Acquiring UMass-Dartmouth Radio Station\"] Ian Donnis, ''RIPR.org'', January 4, 2017</ref><ref>[http://www.umassd.edu/news/2017/wumdriprpartnership.html \"UMass Dartmouth and Rhode Island Public Radio create new collaboration\"] UMass Dartmouth Office of Public Affairs, January 4, 2017</ref><ref>[http://www.radiosurvivor.com/2017/01/04/umass-dartmouth-plans-to-sell-license-for-college-radio-station-wumd-to-rhode-island-public-radio/ \"UMass Dartmouth Plans to Sell License for College Radio Station WUMD to Rhode Island Public Radio\"] Jennifer Waits, ''RadioSurvivor'', January 4, 2017</ref><ref>[http://www.providencejournal.com/news/20170104/ri-public-radio-in-deal-to-get-umass-dartmouth-broadcast-license \"R.I. Public Radio in deal to get UMass Dartmouth broadcast license\"] Aimee Chisvaroll, ''The Standard-Times'', January 4, 2017</ref>  The deal includes a move and [http://mediad.publicbroadcasting.net/p/wrni/files/styles/x_large/public/201701/signal_map.jpg expansion of the existing signal] from the UMassD campus to a taller tower in Tiverton.  The station's FCC [[city of license]] will change from [[North Dartmouth, Massachusetts]] to [[Newport, Rhode Island]].  The existing RIPR network of [[WELH]], [[WCVY]] and [[WNPE (FM)|WNPE]] is not changing as part of this deal.  While not quite a \"statewide\" signal, the new 89.3 will provide one, single frequency that all the [[Narragansett Bay]] and [[South Coast (Massachusetts)|South Coast]] communities can tune to hear the network.  On June 26, 2017 \"WUMD\" ended at noon and transitioned to an online-only station at [http://www.wumd.rocks www.wumd.rocks] and the station went dark for two weeks to add new studio/transmitter link equipment.  89.3 returned to the airwaves with RIPR programming at 10p.m. July 11, 2017.  Construction began on refurbishing the old WLNE tower,<ref>[https://twitter.com/hashtag/WXNI?src=hash \"Tweets showing construction for WXNI/WNPN\"]</ref> and a \"license to cover\" was applied for with the FCC on August 2, 2018<ref>[http://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/forms/prod/prefill_and_display.pl?Application_id=1789812&Service=FM&Form_id=1&Facility_id=163899 \"FCC CDBS application BLED-20180801AAS\"]</ref> indicating imminent operation from the new facility.\n\n'''89.3FM Tiverton:''' on September 1, 2018, the 89.3 [[WNPN]] signal began transmitting full-time from the Tiverton facility.  The move roughly doubles the coverage of the original facility, adding 700,000 new listeners in Rhode Island and the South Coast.\n\nIn October 2018, to reflect its expanded audience, the network rebranded as '''The Public's Radio'''. According to CEO Torey Malatia, branding as merely a Rhode Island service was no longer accurate since it now served Massachusetts as well. After seriously considering changing a name change to \"Southern New England Public Radio,\" network officials decided it was best to choose an identity \"based on what we do as opposed to our zip code.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://radioinsight.com/headlines/171118/rhode-island-public-radio-rebrands-as-the-publics-radio/|title=Rhode Island Public Radio Rebrands As The Public's Radio|date=2018-10-12|work=RadioInsight|access-date=2018-10-13|language=en-US}}</ref> However, the corporate name remains Rhode Island Public Radio.\n\n==Awards==\nRIPR has won over 30 [[Associated Press]] Awards for news coverage, seven [http://prndi.org Public Radio News Directors Inc] Awards, and seven prestigious [http://www.rtdna.org/content/edward_r_murrow_awards RTDNA Edward R. Murrow] Awards.<ref>[http://ripr.org/awards RIPR Awards page.  Page retrieved December 11, 2013.]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|https://thepublicsradio.org/}}\n{{FM station data|WELH}}\n{{FM station data|WCVY}}\n{{FM station data|WNPE}}\n{{FM station data|WNPN}}\n\n{{Providence Radio}}\n{{Newport Radio}}\n{{NPR Rhode Island}}\n{{American broadcast radio}}\n\n[[Category:Radio stations in Rhode Island|*]]\n[[Category:NPR member networks]]\n[[Category:News and talk radio stations in the United States]]\n[[Category:Radio stations established in 1998]]\n[[Category:1998 establishments in Rhode Island]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Public radio network serving Rhode Island}}\n{{Infobox radio station\n|name               = The Public's Radio\n|image              = [[File:Thepublicsradio-logo.jpg|200px|none]]\n|area               = [[Rhode Island]], [[South Coast (Massachusetts)|Massachusetts South Coast]]\n|branding           = \n|slogan             = \n|frequency          = [[WNPN]] 89.3 [[Newport, Rhode Island|Newport]]<br>[[WELH]] 88.1 [[Providence, Rhode Island|Providence]]<br>[[WNPE (FM)|WNPE]] 102.7 [[Narragansett Pier, Rhode Island|Narragansett Pier]]<br>[[WCVY]] 91.5 [[Coventry, Rhode Island|Coventry]]\n|translator         = \n|airdate            = May 1, 1998\n|share              = \n|share as of        = \n|share source       = \n|format             = [[Public Radio]]\n|language           = English\n|affiliations       = [[NPR]]<br>[[Public Radio International]]<br>[[American Public Media]]\n|owner              = Rhode Island Public Radio, Inc\n|licensee           = \n|sister_stations    = \n|webcast            = {{listenlive|http://ripr.org/streaming}}\n|website            = {{URL|https://thepublicsradio.org/}}\n}}\n'''Rhode Island Public Radio''', [[doing business as]] '''The Public's Radio,''' is the [[NPR]] member [[radio network]] for the state of [[Rhode Island]] and southeastern [[Massachusetts]].  Its studios are located in the historic [[Union Station (Providence)|Union Station]] in downtown Providence.  The network airs a format of news and talk from NPR, such as ''[[Morning Edition]]'', ''[[On Point]]'', and ''[[All Things Considered]]'', as well as extensive local news coverage.\n\n==Local programming==\nIn addition to NPR, APM and other public radio programming from national sources, RIPR has dedicated reporters covering specific beats, including [http://ripr.org/programs/politics Politics], [http://ripr.org/programs/pulse Health Care], [http://ripr.org/programs/education-blog Education], the [http://ripr.org/category/environment Environment], and [http://ripr.org/category/arts-culture Arts & Culture].  RIPR also produces local segments including:\n* [http://ripr.org/programs/political-roundtable ''Political Roundtable''] with Ian Donnis, Scott Mackay & Maureen Moakley every Friday.\n* [http://ripr.org/programs/scott-mackays-commentary Scott MacKay's Weekly Commentary'']\n* [http://ripr.org/programs/i-believe-new-england ''This I Believe: New England''] with Frederic Reamer.  A local take on the famous [http://thisibelieve.org ''This I Believe''] series of essays.\n* [http://ripr.org/programs/made-rhode-island ''Made in Rhode Island''] an ongoing occasional series looking at manufacturing in the state.\n* [http://ripr.org/programs/one-square-mile ''One Square Mile''] an annual special week-long series, taking an in-depth look at one city or town in Rhode Island.  Previous OSM series include: Central Falls, Bristol, Woonsocket, West Warwick, Block Island, Narragansett Bay itself, and Newport.\n* [http://ripr.org/policy-and-pinot ''Policy & Pinot''] an ongoing occasional series taped live at the [http://www.providenceathenaeum.org Providence Athenaeum Library] focusing on various topics.\n\n==Broadcast stations==\nThe network's primary signal, [[WNPN]] 89.3FM in [[Newport, Rhode Island|Newport]], broadcasts from the old [[WLNE-TV]] tower in [[Tiverton, Rhode Island|Tiverton]] and covers most of Rhode Island and the [[South Coast (Massachusetts)|Massachusetts South Coast]].  It is the tallest active FM broadcast transmitter in Rhode Island (measured in height above sea level). Only [[WLVO (FM)|WLVO]]'s ''auxiliary'' site on Peck Hill in [[Johnston, Rhode Island]] is taller.\n\nSmaller repeater signals provide additional coverage in Providence ([[WELH]]), South County ([[WNPE (FM)|WNPE]]), and Coventry ([[WCVY]]).\n\n===Technology===\n\n[[WNPN]] transmits using a [[Nautel]] GV15 transmitter with 10,187 watts transmitter power output (TPO) to make 7,000 watts effective radiated power (ERP). A [http://www.shively.com Shively Labs] 6016 four-panel antenna array is used; the antenna is fairly directional, with nulls to avoid prohibited interference to/from [[WQPH]] 89.3FM [[Shirley, Massachusetts]] to the north-northwest, and to [[WPKT]] 89.1FM [[Norwich, Connecticut]] to the west-southwest. An Omnia 9 FM/HD processor from [[The Telos Alliance]] is used to keep audio levels consistent. The station broadcasts in digital [[HD Radio]] although {{as of|2018|8}} no [[multicast]] HD2 or HD3 channels are transmitted. A 67&nbsp;kHz [[subcarrier]] is transmitted for the Massachusetts [[Radio Reading Service]] ''[http://www.audiblelocalledger.org/ Audible Local Ledger]''.\n\n===[[HD Radio]]===\n[[WNPN]] 89.3FM and [[WNPE (FM)|WNPE]] 102.7FM broadcast in [[HD Radio]], simulcasting the analog signal on the HD1 channel.  [[WELH]] 88.1FM and [[WCVY]] 91.5 do not broadcast in HD Radio.\n\nFrom March 2013 until February 2018, [[MVYradio]] leased the HD2 multicast channel of [[WNPE (FM)|WNPE]] to broadcast a modified content stream of [[WMVY]] 88.7FM on Martha's Vineyard, which could also be heard on [[W243AI]] 96.5FM, a lower powered [[FM translator]] transmitting from the roof of Newport Hospital.<ref>[http://ripr.org/post/theec-ripr-mvyradio-leverage-hd-radio-fm-translators RIPR & MVYradio Leverage HD Radio for FM Translators]</ref>  Afterwards, [[WNPE (FM)|WNPE]] discontinued the HD2 broadcast, but continued HD Radio operations for its main HD1 channel.\n\n{| class=\"toccolours\" class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Station\n! Frequency\n! City of license\n! First air date\n! ERP\n! HAAT\n! Facility ID\n! Coordinates\n! Call sign meaning\n! Former call signs\n! Owner\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top; text-align: left;\"\n| '''[[WNPN]]'''\n| 89.3&nbsp;MHz<br>FM & HD\n| [[Newport, Rhode Island|Newport]]\n| June 10, 2006<ref name=\"by2009\">{{cite book|title=Broadcasting & Cable Yearbook 2009|year=2009|page=D-273|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-YB/2009/Radio-GA-MT-BC-YB-2009.pdf|accessdate=August 7, 2018}}</ref>\n| 7,000 watts<br>(directional)\n| {{convert|254|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}\n| 163899\n| {{coord|41|35|48.00|N| 71|11|24.00|W|type:landmark_scale:2000|name=WNPN}}\n| Derived from \"'''N'''ewport, '''P'''rovidence, '''N'''ew Bedford\".\n| WUMD (2006\u20132017)<br>WXNI (2017\u20132018)\n| Rhode Island Public Radio\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top; text-align: left;\"\n| '''WNPE'''\n| 102.7&nbsp;MHz<br>FM & HD\n| [[Narragansett Pier, Rhode Island|Narragansett Pier]]\n| July 15, 1989<ref name=projo-wrnifmstart>1996 Providence Journal Almanac</ref>\n| 1,950 watts<br>(omni)\n| {{convert|69|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}\n| 22874\n| {{coord|41|25|27|N|71|28|38|W|type:landmark_scale:2000|name=WNPE}}\n| Similar to [[WNPN]].\n| WPJB (1989\u20131997)<br>WAKX (1997\u20132007)<br>WRNI-FM (2007-2018)<br>WRNI (2018)\n| Rhode Island Public Radio\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top; text-align: left;\"\n| '''[[WELH]]'''<sup>1</sup>\n| 88.1&nbsp;MHz<br>FM only\n| [[Providence, Rhode Island|Providence]]\n| February 1995\n| 4,000 watts<br>(directional)\n| {{convert|41|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}\n| 66656\n| {{coord|41|51|26.7|N|71|19|5.6|W|type:landmark_scale:2000|name=WELH}}\n| '''W'''h'''E'''e'''L'''er Sc'''H'''ool\n| (none)\n| [[The Wheeler School]]\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top; text-align: left;\"\n| '''[[WCVY]]'''<sup>2</sup>\n| 91.5&nbsp;MHz<br>FM only\n| [[Coventry, Rhode Island|Coventry]]\n| October 19, 1978<ref name=by2003>{{cite book|title=Broadcasting & Cable Yearbook 2003-2004|year=2003|page=D-417|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-YB/2003-04/D-Radio-NE-TER-BC-YB-2003-04.pdf|accessdate=October 10, 2011}}</ref> \n| 200 watts<br>(omni)\n| {{convert|11|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}\n| 14229\n| {{coord|41|41|10|N|71|35|37|W|type:landmark_scale:2000|name=WCVY}}\n| '''C'''o'''V'''entr'''Y'''\n| (none)\n| Coventry Public Schools\n|}\n\nNote:\n*<sup>1</sup> WELH airs student-produced programming from 7pm-10pm Sundays, with The Public's Radio programming airing at all other times.\n*<sup>2</sup> WCVY airs its own programming out of [[Coventry High School (Coventry, Rhode Island)|Coventry High School]] from 2 to 8 p.m. on school days, with The Public's Radio programming airing at all other times.\n* The network's programming is also available on [http://www.fullchannel.com Full Channel Digital Cable] channel 799 in Bristol, Warren and Barrington.\n\n==History==\nIn the 1990s, a group of Rhode Islanders formed the Foundation for Ocean State Public Radio in order to bring a local public radio station to the state. Clare Gregorian was described as the \"driving force\" behind the idea.<ref>http://www.providencejournal.com/news/20180429/clare-gregorian-driving-force-behind-ripr-dies-at-80</ref> At the time, Rhode Island was the only state in [[New England]] (traditionally one of the bedrocks of support for NPR) and one of only two in the entire country (the other being [[Delaware]]) that did not have a full-service NPR station within its borders. Most of the state got at least a grade B signal from Boston's [[WGBH (FM)|WGBH]] (with Providence itself receiving a city-grade signal) and [[WBUR]].  After a few years of looking, they found a partner in [[Boston University]], owner of WBUR.  BU agreed to buy [[WRPA (AM)|WRCP]] (1290 [[AM broadcasting|AM]]), a 5,000-watt station that had been on the air since [[1947 in radio|1947]], for $1.9 million; the foundation conducted a statewide drive to help raise the funds.  For many years, 1290 AM had been known as WICE, but switched to [[Portugal|Portuguese]] programming as WRCP in [[1983 in radio|1983]].\n\nOn May 1, 1998, WRCP's calls officially changed to WRNI, and the license was officially transferred to the '''WRNI Foundation,''' a separate fundraising group set up by WBUR to handle local underwriting.\n\nEven though BU doubled WRNI's transmission power to 10,000 watts, its signal was not strong enough to reach the southern and western portion of the state (though it provides a city-grade signal to [[Newport, Rhode Island|Newport]], southern Rhode Island's biggest city).  Accordingly, in 1999, BU bought WERI (1230 AM) in Westerly, which had been on the air since [[1949 in radio|1949]].  BU changed WERI's calls to WXNI, and made it a full-time satellite of WRNI.  The station brought a city-grade NPR signal to southern Rhode Island for the first time ever.\n\nBU and WBUR had very big plans for WRNI at first. It moved WRNI from its longtime studio on Douglas Avenue to a state-of-the-art facility at Union Station.  It also started a daily two-hour local news magazine, ''One Union Station.''  <ref name=\"Fybush\">[http://www.fybush.com/NERW/2004/040920/nerw.html NorthEast Radio Watch by Scott Fybush<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>  It also had plans to set up a third station to fill the gaps in WXNI's 1,000-watt signal.<ref name=\"Current\">[http://www.current.org/radio/radio0418rhodeisland.shtml Current.org | Struggle over WBUR's Rhode Island stations, 2004<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> However, budget problems brought on by the [[September 11, 2001 attacks]] forced ''One Union Station's'' cancellation. It was replaced with a one-hour news magazine that was canceled in 2004. At that point, WRNI's local operations were significantly cut back, with most of the station's staff either laid off or transferred to Boston. As a result, WRNI's schedule became almost identical to that of WBUR.\n\n===Controversy over sale of 1290AM===\nOn September 17, 2004, with no advance warning, WBUR Group general manager Jane Christo announced that WRNI and WXNI were being put on the market. She wouldn't give any specifics, only saying that it was time for Rhode Islanders to buy the stations if they wanted to keep NPR programming in the state.<ref name=\"Fybush\"/>  Indeed, WBUR claimed that it never intended to operate WRNI on a long-term basis, and had only intended to help develop it into a self-sustaining service.<ref name=\"Current\"/>\n\nThe reaction in Rhode Island was, not surprisingly, hostile. In an editorial, ''[[The Providence Journal]]'' said that WBUR had made numerous long-term commitments to WRNI. The ''Journal'' claimed that if the station's local backers had to buy WRNI, it would be tantamount to buying the station twice.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.projo.com/opinion/editorials/content/projo_20040919_19edwr.10caf3.html|title=Editorial: Broadcast betrayal |work=Providence Journal|date=September 19, 2004|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080301105211/http://www.projo.com/opinion/editorials/content/projo_20040919_19edwr.10caf3.html|archivedate=March 1, 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe announcement led state attorney general [[Patrick C. Lynch|Patrick Lynch]] to open an investigation into WBUR and WRNI.<ref name=\"LynchGlobe\">{{cite news|author=Peoples, Steve| url=http://www.beloblog.com/ProJo_Blogs/newsblog/archives/2006/11/attorney_genera_1.html | title=Attorney general closes WBUR investigation | work=Providence Journal|date=November 20, 2006|accessdate=September 22, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn September 27, BU interim president [[Aram Chobanian]] delayed the sale of WRNI and WXNI, citing concerns raised by both Lynch and [[Governor of Rhode Island|Rhode Island Governor]] [[Don Carcieri]].  Memos obtained by ''[[The Boston Globe]]'' revealed that WBUR felt the Rhode Island stations were money bleeders, and had decided to either lease or sell the stations at the earliest opportunity.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.boston.com/ae/tv/articles/2004/09/28/bu_delays_sale_of_ri_radio_stations | work=The Boston Globe | first=Mark | last=Jurkowitz | title=BU delays sale of R.I. radio stations | date=September 28, 2004}}</ref>  The furor over the WRNI sale was one factor in Christo's resignation almost a month later.<ref>[http://www.current.org/radio/radio0419wbur.shtml Current.org | Christo resigns at WBUR, 2004<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nIn June [[2005 in radio|2005]], BU took WRNI and WXNI off the market.  It promised to hire a full-time general manager based in Providence, and also stepped up local news coverage.  As a result, Lynch closed his investigation in November 2006.<ref name=\"LynchGlobe\"/>\n\n===Independence from Boston University===\nOn March 21, 2007, WBUR announced that it was selling WRNI to Rhode Island Public Radio (formerly the Foundation for Ocean State Public Radio) for $2 million. Rhode Island Public Radio also announced it was buying WAKX (102.7 [[FM broadcasting|FM]]) in [[Narragansett Pier, Rhode Island|Narragansett Pier]] from [[Davidson Media Group]] to serve as a repeater for WRNI in southern Rhode Island.<ref>{{cite news|author=Smith, Andy| url=http://green.tmcnet.com/news/2007/03/23/2439642.htm| title=R.I. group to buy WRNI|date=March 23, 2007|work=Providence Journal}}</ref> WAKX, which signed on in 1989, had been a [[smooth jazz]] station (though its call letters referred to a former simulcast of [[WWKX]], which lasted from 1997 to 2005).  As part of the sale agreement, BU will continue to provide engineering and programming assistance to RIPR for five years.\n\nRIPR officially took control of WAKX on May 17, 2007; changing the calls to WRNI-FM. The addition of WRNI-FM made WXNI redundant, and BU has sold that station separately to Diponti Communications, which renamed it [[WBLQ (AM)|WBLQ]].  RIPR took control of WRNI on September 1, 2008.\n\nRIPR registered the domain name ''ripr.org'' on February 13, 2007; the site was live as of June 2007.\n\n===Migration to FM===\n[[File:WNPN Air Studio.jpg|thumb|right|The Public's Radio Studio A, where local newscasts originate daily.]]\nRecognizing the long-term challenges of AM broadcasting,<ref>[http://www.radioworld.com/news-and-business/0002/is-am-radio-still-relevant/322673 \"Is AM Radio Still Relevant?\" Radio World, August 30, 2009]</ref> and the general expectation by public radio listeners that public radio stations transmit on the noncommercial end of the FM band (88.1-91.9&nbsp;MHz), in 2011 WRNI began to expand into a statewide network of FM signals.  Accordingly, it also began branding itself exclusively as \"Rhode Island Public Radio.\"\n\n'''91.5FM''' First, in July 2011, RIPR entered an agreement with [[WCVY]] (91.5 FM), which is owned & operated by [[Coventry High School (Coventry, Rhode Island)|Coventry High School]] and covers the Kent County region. Previously, because WCVY did not broadcast 24/7, they had been forced, under [https://www.law.cornell.edu/cfr/text/47/73.561 FCC rule 73.561(b)], to \"share-time\" 16 hours per day of the frequency with the now-defunct [[Religious broadcasting|religious]] station [[WRJI]]. After WRJI lost its license, RIPR assisted WCVY in \"reclaiming\" the frequency for 24/7 operation.  WCVY still airs its own student-created programming on weekdays from 2-8p.m. when school is in session, and RIPR fills the remainder of the time to avoid another \"share-time\" challenge.<ref name=nerw-wcvyripr>{{cite news|last=Fybush|first=Scott|authorlink=|title=Merlin Drops 101.9 Clues|url=http://www.fybush.com/NERW/2011/110711/nerw.html|accessdate=October 10, 2011|newspaper=NorthEast Radio Watch|date=July 11, 2011}}</ref>\n\n'''88.1FM''' Then, on October 8, 2011, RIPR signed a 10-year lease with [[The Wheeler School]], a K-12 private day school and owner of [[WELH]] (88.1 FM).<ref>[http://www.radiosurvivor.com/2011/08/22/the-wheeler-school-to-lease-fm-airwaves-to-rhode-island-public-radio/ \"The Wheeler School to Lease FM Airwaves to Rhode Island Public Radio\"] Jennifer Waits, ''Radio Survivor'', August 22, 2011</ref> RIPR's content would be heard 24/7 on 88.1 in Providence except for a student-produced sports talk radio midnight-3 Saturday mornings.  The remainder of Wheeler's student media was migrated to internet radio and, more recently, to [http://www.wheelerschoolbroadcasting.org/ internet video projects].\n\nAs part of this new lease, the previous lease tenants on 88.1, [[WBRU-LP|Brown Student Radio]], and [[Latino Public Radio]], each broadcasting a limited number of hours each day, were displaced:\n\n*BSR began an internet radio station \"[http://www.bsrlive.com BSRlive]\" and, in January 2015, was granted an FCC license for an LPFM station [https://fccdata.org/?facid=&call=wbru&ccode=1&city=&state=&country=US&arn=&party=&party_type=LICEN WBRU-LP] on 101.1FM in Providence, in conjunction with [[Providence Community Radio]] and [[AS220]].<ref name=bsr-lpfm>{{cite news|last=Ahlquist|first=Steve|title=New low-power FM community radio station coming to Providence|url=http://www.rifuture.org/new-low-power-fm-community-radio-station-coming-to-providence/|accessdate=November 13, 2015|newspaper=RIfuture.org|date=November 13, 2015}}</ref><ref>[https://as220.org/101-1-fm-community-radio/ \"AS220: 101.1 FM Community Radio!\"] November 9, 2015</ref>\n*Latino Public Radio signed a lease with RIPR to broadcast on RIPR's 1290AM signal, WRNI,<ref name=projo-wrnishuffle>{{cite news|last=Ziner|first=Karen Lee|title=R.I. Latino radio station going 24/7 in new place|url=http://www.projo.com/news/content/LATINO_PUBLIC_RADIO_10-07-11_R4QO3C9_v29.70439.html|accessdate=October 10, 2011|newspaper=[[The Providence Journal]]|date=October 7, 2011|archiveurl=http://www.latinopublicradioconsortium.org/index.php?s=7394&item=21203|archivedate=October 7, 2011}}</ref><ref name=rinpr-wrnishuffle>{{cite news|last=Harrison|first=Elisabeth|title=Changes ahead for radio in Rhode Island|url=http://www.publicbroadcasting.net/wrni/news.newsmain/article/0/0/1861788/Top.Stories/Changes.ahead.for.radio.in.Rhode.Island|accessdate=October 10, 2011|newspaper=WRNI.org|date=October 10, 2011}}</ref> and moved to 1290AM the same day RIPR moved to 88.1FM.  In addition to allowing LPR to broadcast 24/7, it also gave them a larger signal.<ref>Until late 2010, WELH was only a 150-watt signal, much smaller than the 4, 000-watt signal it is today. See [http://fccdata.org/?appid=205223&facid=66656 \"FCCdata.org file on WELH\"] and [http://fccdata.org/?facid=48308 \"FCCdata.org file on WRNI-AM\"] for comparison.</ref>\n\n'''89.3FM:''' Most recently, in January 2017, RIPR announced a deal with the [[University of Massachusetts, Dartmouth]] to purchase [[WNPN|WUMD]] (89.3 FM).<ref>[http://ripr.org/post/ri-public-radio-acquiring-umass-dartmouth-radio-station \"RI Public Radio Acquiring UMass-Dartmouth Radio Station\"] Ian Donnis, ''RIPR.org'', January 4, 2017</ref><ref>[http://www.umassd.edu/news/2017/wumdriprpartnership.html \"UMass Dartmouth and Rhode Island Public Radio create new collaboration\"] UMass Dartmouth Office of Public Affairs, January 4, 2017</ref><ref>[http://www.radiosurvivor.com/2017/01/04/umass-dartmouth-plans-to-sell-license-for-college-radio-station-wumd-to-rhode-island-public-radio/ \"UMass Dartmouth Plans to Sell License for College Radio Station WUMD to Rhode Island Public Radio\"] Jennifer Waits, ''RadioSurvivor'', January 4, 2017</ref><ref>[http://www.providencejournal.com/news/20170104/ri-public-radio-in-deal-to-get-umass-dartmouth-broadcast-license \"R.I. Public Radio in deal to get UMass Dartmouth broadcast license\"] Aimee Chisvaroll, ''The Standard-Times'', January 4, 2017</ref>  The deal includes a move and [http://mediad.publicbroadcasting.net/p/wrni/files/styles/x_large/public/201701/signal_map.jpg expansion of the existing signal] from the UMassD campus to a taller tower in Tiverton.  The station's FCC [[city of license]] will change from [[North Dartmouth, Massachusetts]] to [[Newport, Rhode Island]].  The existing RIPR network of [[WELH]], [[WCVY]] and [[WNPE (FM)|WNPE]] is not changing as part of this deal.  While not quite a \"statewide\" signal, the new 89.3 will provide one, single frequency that all the [[Narragansett Bay]] and [[South Coast (Massachusetts)|South Coast]] communities can tune to hear the network.  On June 26, 2017 \"WUMD\" ended at noon and transitioned to an online-only station at [http://www.wumd.rocks www.wumd.rocks] and the station went dark for two weeks to add new studio/transmitter link equipment.  89.3 returned to the airwaves with RIPR programming at 10p.m. July 11, 2017.  Construction began on refurbishing the old WLNE tower,<ref>[https://twitter.com/hashtag/WXNI?src=hash \"Tweets showing construction for WXNI/WNPN\"]</ref> and a \"license to cover\" was applied for with the FCC on August 2, 2018<ref>[http://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/forms/prod/prefill_and_display.pl?Application_id=1789812&Service=FM&Form_id=1&Facility_id=163899 \"FCC CDBS application BLED-20180801AAS\"]</ref> indicating imminent operation from the new facility.\n\n'''89.3FM Tiverton:''' on September 1, 2018, the 89.3 [[WNPN]] signal began transmitting full-time from the Tiverton facility.  The move roughly doubles the coverage of the original facility, adding 700,000 new listeners in Rhode Island and the South Coast.\n\nIn October 2018, to reflect its expanded audience, the network rebranded as '''The Public's Radio'''. According to CEO Torey Malatia, branding as merely a Rhode Island service was no longer accurate since it now served Massachusetts as well. After seriously considering changing a name change to \"Southern New England Public Radio,\" network officials decided it was best to choose an identity \"based on what we do as opposed to our zip code.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://radioinsight.com/headlines/171118/rhode-island-public-radio-rebrands-as-the-publics-radio/|title=Rhode Island Public Radio Rebrands As The Public's Radio|date=2018-10-12|work=RadioInsight|access-date=2018-10-13|language=en-US}}</ref> However, the corporate name remains Rhode Island Public Radio.\n\n==Awards==\nRIPR has won over 30 [[Associated Press]] Awards for news coverage, seven [http://prndi.org Public Radio News Directors Inc] Awards, and seven prestigious [http://www.rtdna.org/content/edward_r_murrow_awards RTDNA Edward R. Murrow] Awards.<ref>[http://ripr.org/awards RIPR Awards page.  Page retrieved December 11, 2013.]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|https://thepublicsradio.org/}}\n{{FM station data|WELH}}\n{{FM station data|WCVY}}\n{{FM station data|WNPE}}\n{{FM station data|WNPN}}\n\n{{Providence Radio}}\n{{Newport Radio}}\n{{NPR Rhode Island}}\n\n[[Category:Radio stations in Rhode Island|*]]\n[[Category:NPR member networks]]\n[[Category:News and talk radio stations in the United States]]\n[[Category:Radio stations established in 1998]]\n[[Category:1998 establishments in Rhode Island]]\n", "name_user": "Ben76266", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Public%27s_Radio"}
